class Solution {
    public boolean canBeEqual(int[] target, int[] arr) {
        int n = target.length;
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            if (target[i] != arr[i]) {
                return false;
            }
        }
        return true;
    }
}
```

efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n)
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW

Explanation:

The problem requires comparing each element of the target array with the corresponding element in the arr array. Since there are n elements in both arrays, the time complexity is O(n). The space complexity is O(1) because we only use a constant amount of space for the arrays themselves. The energy implications are low because no additional energy-consuming operations are performed.

